04404nam a22005895i 9780889209411DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20062002xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97808892094117 a10.51644/97808892094112doi  a(DE-B1597)667483  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aCT25b.B877 2002 7aPSY0100002bisacsh04a809.9359207222200aRepossessing the World :bReading Memoirs by Contemporary Women /ced. by Helen M. Buss. 1aWaterloo, Ontario : bWilfrid Laurier University Press, c[2006] 4c©2002  a1 online resource (231 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLife Writing00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgements -- tAn Autobiocritical Preface -- tIntroduction -- tMemoir with an Attitude -- tIdentity As a Balancing Act -- tDancing with Our Mothers -- t“Scenes of Language” -- tJoining Heart and Head -- tConclusion -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex -- tBooks in the Life Writing Series Published0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhy does it seem as if everyone is writing memoirs, and particularly women? The current popularity of memoir verifies the common belief that we each have a story to tell. And we do.especially women. Memoirs are not only representations of women’s personal lives but also of their desire to repossess important parts of our culture, in which women’s stories have not mattered. Beginning with her own motivations for writing memoirs, Helen M. Buss examines the many kinds of memoir written by contemporary women: memoirs about growing up, memoirs about traumatic events, about relationships, about work. In writing memoirs, these women publicly assert that their lives have mattered. They reshape the memoir, a form as old as the middle ages and as young as today, into a social discourse that blends the personal with the political, the self with the significant other, literature with history, and fiction with autobiography and essay. Buss urges readers to use their reading experience to help themselves understand and write the significance of their own lives. Repossessing the World is the first book-length critical inquiry into women’s use of a form that has often been dismissed as less important than autobiography, less professional than the novel, and less intellectual than the formal essay. Buss demonstrates that the memoir makes its own art, not only through selective borrowing from these genres but also through the unique way that the tripartite narrative voice of the memoir constructs the personal and public experience of the memorist as significant to our cultural moment.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAutobiographyxWomen authors. 0aLiterature, Moderny20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aProse literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aWomenvBiographyxHistory and criticism. 4aBiography & Autobiography. 4aLife Writing. 4aSocial Science: Women’s Studies. 7aPSYCHOLOGY / Psychotherapy / Counseling.2bisacsh1 aBuss, Helen M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978088920941140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780889209411423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780889209411/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles